</style></head>
  <body id="s">
    <ul>
      <li>Animals can produce glucose from sugars or proteins</li>
    </ul>
    <p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; - Sugars: pyruvate, lactate, or oxaloacetate<br>
      &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; - Protein: from amino acids that can be converted to
      citric acid cycle intermediates (or glucogenic amino acids) <br>
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li> Animals cannot produce glucose from fatty acids</li>
    </ul>
    <p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; - Product of fatty acid degradation is acetyl-CoA<br>
      &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; - Cannot have a net conversion of acetyl-CoA to
      oxaloacetate</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Plants, yeast, and many bacteria can have a net conversion of
        acetyl-CoA to oxaloacetate, thus producing glucose from fatty acids</li>
    </ul>
  </body>
